lts to public. I’m considering adding a test called `supportsInlineExpressionsInValueAndKeyInterpolations`. I want to avoid duplication, so I’m pondering whether we need to retest collection maps. \\n\\nIf we use pure expressions for computed keys and Json values, that might work better. For instance, I can use the syntax `${...}` to involve inline expressions. I’m thinking of covering those scenarios, but I also need to check that everything is compatible with existing encoders.\"},{\"type\":\"summary_text\",\"text\":\"**Exploring key position interpolation**\\n\\nI'm considering the scenario where an expression in an interpolation key position isn't a string, such as `${40 + 2}`. This would mean it exercises the KeyEncoder[Int], which hasn’t been tested yet. The existing SectionName key is custom and does not use Int. The upstream details mention non-string variables, but the current setup only handles custom keys. This new feature could allow interpolation of non-string object keys with a standard KeyEncoder, blending arbitrary inline expressions with non-string keys.\"}]}"}, {"type": "toolCall", "id": "call_3kAWkxdaDWH76cQ6NWpdRgd7|fc_0491e1836eb393f3016a2a559c9aa081958a22f9b308eee7f9", "name": "edit", "arguments": {"path": "tests/src/io.circe/circe-literal_3/0.14.15/src/test/scala/io_circe/circe_literal_3/Circe_literal_3Test.scala", "edits": [{"oldText": "  @Test\n  def supportsTopLevelInterpolatedEncodedValues(): Unit = {", "newText": "  @Test\n  def supportsInlineExpressionsInInterpolatedKeysAndValues(): Unit = {\n    val first: Int = 21\n    val second: Int = 2\n\n    val document: Json = json\"\"\"\n      {\n        ${first * second}: ${List(1, 2, 3).map(_ * second)},\n        \"computed\": ${(\"circe\" + \"-literal\").toUpperCase},\n        \"enabled\": ${first < second}\n      }\n      \"\"\"\n    val cursor = document.hcursor\n\n    assertEquals(List(2, 4, 6), expectRight(cursor.get[List[Int]](\"42\")))\n    assertEquals(\"CIRCE-LITERAL\", expectRight(cursor.get[String](\"computed\")))\n    assertFalse(expectRight(cursor.get[Boolean](\"enabled\")))\n  }\n\n  @Test\n  def supportsTopLevelInterpolatedEncodedValues(): Unit = {"}]}}], "api": "openai-responses", "provider": "OCA", "model": "oca/gpt-5.5", "usage": {"input": 1420, "output": 1782, "cacheRead": 28160, "cacheWrite": 0, "totalTokens": 31362, "cost": {"input": 0, "output": 0, "cacheRead": 0, "cacheWrite": 0, "total": 0}}, "stopReason": "toolUse", "timestamp": 1781159286063, "responseId": "resp_0491e1836eb393f3016a2a5576b1ec8195bf66e17e3c992cbd"}}
